{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/576"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.21,0.49,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54202"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39678"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3915"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54202"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to hospital with a three week history of worsening bilateral leg pain and weakness that today resulted in a fall. This is in the context of a six month history of haemoptysis, weight loss and anorexia. He is continent of his bladder and bowels. His medical history includes chronic back pain, hypertension, and benign prostatic hypertrophy. He is a current smoker of 20 cigarettes/day. On examination, there is wasting of his right hypothenar eminence, right-sided ptosis and fixed miosis. Neurological examination of the lower limb demonstrates reduced power 4/5 primarily in the proximal muscle groups and reduced reflexes. His vibration, proprioception and light touch sensation are intact. His anal tone is intact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most useful investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Spinal MRI","CT chest, abdomen, pelvis","Vitamin B12 levels","Electromyography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is strong clinical suspicion for lung cancer causing this patient\u0027s current\u00a0presentation, given his\u00a0six-month history of haemoptysis, constitutional symptoms\u00a0and significant smoking status. It is likely that the\u00a0apical lung cancer\u00a0has already affected the T1 nerve root, causing wasting of his right hypothenar eminence. His ptosis and fixed miosis implies that there is also interruption of the sympathetic nerve supply to the eye at this level of the spinal cord (Horner\u2019s syndrome). His worsening bilateral leg\u00a0weakness\u00a0(proximal myopathy)\u00a0but with continence of bladder and bowels and preserved anal tone\u00a0is suggestive of paraneoplastic myopathy (Lambert Eaton syndrome) as a result of his lung cancer, as opposed to cauda equina syndrome from spinal cord metastases. The most\u00a0appropriate investigation\u00a0is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis \u003C/strong\u003Eto look for\u00a0a lung\u00a0malignancy and evaluate for metastases.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a chest X-ray might be the initial investigation, it would not not be the most useful investigation in these circumstances. A chest X-ray might miss a lung cancer\u00a0due to poorer resolution - but more importantly, would be of limited value in looking for evidence of the suspected metastatic disease.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpinal MRI would be more appropriate as an initial investigation if there were suspicion for cauda equina syndrome; however, this is not likely due to preservation of anal tone, and continence of bladder and bowels.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectromyography is not the most appropriate investigation for this patient\u2019s proximal myopathy, as when considered in context of his other symptoms, he needs urgent investigation to identify an underlying malignancy.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency is associated with a peripheral neuropathy that affects the dorsal columns, manifesting with impaired vibration and proprioception. This patient has no features of vitamin B12 deficiency and so it is not an appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An underlying malignancy should always be considered when a patient presents with unexplained muscle weakness."],"references":["Lancaster E. Paraneoplastic disorders.\u00a0Continuum (Minneap Minn). 2015; 21:452-75."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39678"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"576"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39678"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T08:46:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T08:47:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54202"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":